Subject: [R-sig-teaching] demonstration of weaknesses in stepwise variable
 selection
Message-ID: <485396B7-761E-499D-B580-BF7D3E912354@me.com>

I am developing a short presentation for people with applied statistical backgrounds who have used backward stepwise variable selection where they remove variables based on small coefficient values, coefficient P values > 0.05, and large variances.

I am wanting to provide some demonstration code in R that highlights some of the weakness as described by Frank Harrell (citation below). 

Of particular interest are (1) failure to include informative predictor variables (categorical and continuous) and (2) lowered standard errors for the coefficients in the final model. I have code to demonstrate inclusion of too many false predictors.

I expect this code is available, but I have not found it. Guidance would be appreciated.

Mark
P.S. I have started a public github package at https://github.com/rmsharp/stepwiser
I has very little in it thus far.


Frank E. Harrell. Regression Modeling Strategies with applications to linear models, logistic regression, and survival analysis, Springer Series in Statistics. Springer-Verlag. 2015.


